Since his first race in 2006, Sass has placed in over 20 races, including several first place finishes.

Last month he won 1,000-mile Yukon Quest International Sled Dog Race.

The Iditarod began Monday in Fairbanks and will finish in Nome. 

Aliy Zirkle of Two Rivers was in the lead 227 miles into the race Tuesday at the Tanana checkpoint, where Sass is currently resting. 

The  fastest winning record was set in 2014 by Dallas Seavey with a time of eight days, 13 hours, four minutes, and 19 seconds.

